                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">Here's my idea (that I formulated while responding to Nanyea's suggestions on eqlive board):
<br />

<br />
We know what the problems with the class are:
<br />

<br />
1. Not the best slowers in the world partly because of the need to tash and its very high agro.  Also because mitigated slow tends to reduce effectiveness of higher pct vs lower pct slows.  Also because our survivability on slow resist agro is lower than all other slowers (Shaman, Bard, Beastlords).
<br />

<br />
2. Charm dps reduction (70-80 pct) in OoW expansion eliminates functionality of enchanter dps.
<br />

<br />
3. Long-term trend to out-of-camp crowd control eliminating the need for, and reducing the utility of, mez.  Lull / Pacify less effective in some situations (Hard LDoN - possibly some other zones with high hitters).
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
Taken together, 1-3 make enchanters much less useful as a group exp member and active raid participant (except in encounters where mez or charm dps is highlighted by developers - e.g. Rathe Council, RZtW, etc).
<br />

<br />
Giving us a "better" slow (i.e. faster casting) or merely reducing Tash agro to that of Malo - would only address our role as slowers in exp group.  Many enchanters are not satisfied with tash, slow, nuke, nuke, repeat role during the xp grind.  It also does nothing for us on raids, where Shaman are present.  Additionally, making us better slowers could have negative impact on desirability of shaman class in groups (and I think that class has enough problems).
<br />

<br />
Assuming charm dps is not adjusted (lack of response to our concerns so far make this increasingly likely, imo), what is left for the future of the enchanter?
<br />

<br />
They can either:
<br />
A. Re-design the whole game to make it more like Kunark (more mobs with lower dps) - something they have stated they won't do
<br />
B. Improve enchanter out-of-group CC functionality
<br />

<br />
In my "fix" I am addressing B:
<br />

<br />
Give enchanters Fade.  This has multiple positive impacts:
<br />

<br />
1. Makes enchanters pullers in high-dps content areas.  In normal LDoN, I shined as a puller.  Low resist rate on pacify plus the fact that I could not be one-rounded by the mobs, enabled me to do the job.  In hard LDoN, my inability to drop agro and the higher resist rate on pacify prevents this.
<br />

<br />
2. Improves enchanter survivability on resists - whether it be while slowing or mezzing.  I don't resent other classes having a faster casting slow.  I do resent being one and a half rounded on a slow resist.
<br />

<br />
3. Gives the group alternative to doing CC out of camp.  If an enchanter can survive a mez resist, then in-camp crowd control (as an option - not a requirement for the group) becomes viable again - and its viable without kiting or rooting the add(s).  E.G. - monk tells group - going to be two.  Enchanter tells the group - no problem.  Out-of-camp CC = boring.  In-camp CC = FUN.  Believe me, we aren't the only classes that miss the fun and challenge of KC, Chardok, and Sebilis.
<br />

<br />
Downsides of this ability to other classes:  I don't see any that are significant.  Shaman are still desirable for better slow and buffs (and the new avoidance buffs in OoW are wonderful).  Bards are still desirable for tracking, better (i.e. faster) overall slow, and other group benefits.  Rangers are still desirable for tracking and dps.  Would enchanters replace monks as pullers across the board?  Honestly, I don't see that happening.  Much is wrong with the monk class - I don't see that many enchanters being interested in the pulling aspect of this ability to supercede their role as pullers.  Besides - there are limits to the Fade ability (like fading while still in agro range) that still make monk FD the best pulling ability around.  Fade won't make chanters the best pullers - it will just make pulling possible.
<br />

<br />
Now - what about raid utility you may ask?  I'm not done yet.  FD is the primary pull ability used indoor.  One sees Bards and Rangers pull at raids.  I've pulled on Grummus, BoT towers, etc etc and without Fade (but only where pac works).  In most cases, there is no shortage of pullers on raids.  So what is it chanters can do?
<br />

<br />
Make enchanter Fade targetable, in-group only.  This ability has uses both in groups and on raids:
<br />

<br />
1. In xp group - Tank dies, cleric starts getting pounded, Fade the cleric - next on mob hate list has agro and the group has a chance not to wipe.
<br />

<br />
2. Raiding LMM - mob is at 60 pct and MT /rs defensive down in 10 seconds.  Chanter (in group) fades the MT and the Secondary with defensive up takes over.
<br />

<br />
3. Raiding - group member (wizard) is summoned - Chanter Fades them and they can back off if they weren't one-rounded.
<br />

<br />
What's interesting about this ability is it is very, very active.  Unless you're one of those boxers with incredible hotkeys and extreme attentiveness - its very hard to react quickly enough for this ability to be used effectively on a "bot".
<br />

<br />
The ability is also limited, by making it in-group only.  Out-of-group bot can't affect group members.
<br />

<br />
Is it "overpowering"?  It could be - definitely needs some limits on it.  Right now I'm seeing it as something that enables things to be done another way - rather than enabling something to be done that couldn't before.  
<br />

<br />
In my example of LMM and defensive going down - currently the SA warrior and MT could coordinate that with 10 sec left the MT calls and stops attacking / taunting and the SA AE taunts for agro.  Does targeted Fade make this less tricky?  I'm not sure.
<br />

<br />
In my example of someone being summoned, an on-the-spot group member or two could hit them with a fast heal to keep them up.
<br />

<br />
How do we implement this ability so it isn't completely overpowering?  It needs a few limits:
<br />

<br />
1. Targetable - in-group only (no killing another group by fading their tank - and limits the ability's effectiveness on raids)
<br />

<br />
2. High mana cost - I'm starting with the idea of 1500 mana.  Many high level, pre-elemental geared enchanters have mana pools around 4-5K.  OoW levels by themselves don't seem to increase the mana pool that much.  If you're 5K buffed, that's 3 uses (6 with GM but that's a long re-use)
<br />

<br />
3. Recast timer - I'm starting with the idea of once per minute.  Got a bad pull?  Fade and wait one minute before trying again.  Fade off cleric agro?  You have 1 minute before fading them again.  Same on slow resist.
<br />

<br />
4. AA or spell gem?  Make it take up a spell slot.  Make it a questable spell (without flag requirements).  Hell, it could be harder than epic 1.0 and I would still do it.  My preference? put in the PoK library required level 65 <img src="images/smiles/icon_biggrin.gif" alt="icon_biggrin.gif" border="0" />  
<br />

<br />
What are your thoughts (besides, "SoE will never give it to us.")?  Would it make the class fun for you again?  Does it make other classes severely less desirable?  Is 1500 mana not enough or too much?  Is 1 minute recast not long enough?  Is the targetable effect too overpowering?  Does it lend itself to exploits on raids?</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="color: darkblue"> 
<br />
